<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>SSE submission to the Energy and Climate Change Committee Enquiry on Low Carbon Innovation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by SSE (LCI0008)</span></h1><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSE is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a UK owned and based energy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">company. It is the UK’s second largest energy generator and the largest generator of energy from renewable sources. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSE invested £5.7m in R&amp;D in 2012/13 and £11.2m in 2011/12. SSE’s approach to research is collaborative and it has received external fundi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ng; as such it is involved in projects with a value much higher than its direct cash contribution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In general SSE deploys technology rather than developing it. Its primary interest is in the demonstration and commercialisation stages, or higher Technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Readiness Levels (TRLs).</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary </span></h2><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Level of innovation funding</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The recent NAO report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> noted that energy innovation spend as a proportion of GDP is relatively low in the UK, and that energy R&amp;D spend has fallen significantly since 1980. Given t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he scale of the challenges that the energy system now faces in transitioning to a lower carbon system and sustaining unprecedented levels of investment, investment in R&amp;D should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSE recommends that any increase in funding should be directed in large part towards demonstration activities, where important lessons regarding business models, commercialisation and know-how are learnt in addition to technical knowledge. Without this sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ge, many innovations will not proceed irrespective of their merits. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All of this needs to be underpinned by a stable policy framework that provides a reasonable prospect of successful innovations being able to find a market.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Funding landscape</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We note </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that the funding landscape remains complicated and could be rationalised.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">re are two particular anomalies: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are now an extremely significant funder of energy research, but they are still learning how to be a collaborative funding body alongside t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">heir separate role as a regulator.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> We note the recent Energy Research and Training Prospectus</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recommendation that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should be a full LCICG member, for example.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ETI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is an unusual public-private organisation. SSE has concerns about the governance of ETI because the sharing of knowledge is controlled to a large extent by the private ETI members. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Answers to specific questions</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Will the Government’s current approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">towards low carbon innovation help to achieve the UK’s legally binding targets at the lowest possible cost?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Government’s current approach will help, but it is clearly only part of the answer. The biggest challenge to meeting the UK’s targets is policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> uncertainty, and this is not always well joined-up with the funding landscape. For example, recently a new call for funding for offsho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">renewables</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">shortly after</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> National Grid scenarios in support of EMR with dramatically red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uced ambition for o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ffshore wind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is no point in funding demonstration projects for technologies that have no chance of achieving market pull through to commercialisation. In the increasingly policy-driven world of energy, that means having a supportive policy framewo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rk. This suggests that Government should be considering end-to-end pathways from early research through to supportive policies. Of course it is not possible to map out a perfect roadmap for every technology from its first steps, but currently it appears th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">at the policy development at one end is largely independent of the research support at the other.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2. Does the Government have the right balance of focus between energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSE supports the efforts of the TINA process to make comparisons across, as well as within, themes; this should help achieve the right balance. We note that the funding available to electricity networks facilitated by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> represents a significant proport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ion of overall energy innovation funding, and that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is merely an observer in the LCICG that produces the TINAs. It could be argued that this level of funding is out of balance, although SSE would recommend restoring that balance by increasing funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in other areas rather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">than reducing networks funding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The balance between research stages (e.g. basic research, applied research, demonstration) is as important as the balance between thematic areas (see Q4).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSE recommends consideration of the whole sys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tem to understand the linkages between the three identified themes, and those research activities that cut across multiple themes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What outcomes, if any, are the LCICG likely to achieve? How should its forthcoming strategy drive more investment into low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">carbon innovation, and how should it measure success?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The LCICG has improved coordination between funding bodies, which is welcome. Nevertheless, the funding landscape remains complicated and the LCICG can only advise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> coordinate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and provide evidence: it remains up to the individual funding bodies to choose how to use their own funds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The LCICG is necessar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">y because the landscape is over-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">complicated and therefore suboptimal. Rationalisation could reduce or remove the need for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCICG.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Are the Government &amp; LCICG targeting investment towards the most effective stages of the innovation process, including over the long-term?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All stages of the innovation process may require support and public intervention. We note that energy innova</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tion is under-funded, so we would not wish to see support for any stage reduced. If additional funding was made available, it should be directed primarily at later-stage innovation, which is expensive but a crucial step in bringing new products to market a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nd developing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">understanding of business models, policy requirements and so on. SSE conducts this type of project, many of which would not proceed without external funding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. What is the impact of the short-term funding timelines on private sector investm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ent?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A long-term approach to funding enables companies to invest more in resources to take a more proactive approach towards funding innovation. For example, SSE has created a full time post to work on Horizon 2020, the budget for which has been agreed fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">om 2014-2020. Note that we do not necessarily need to know the details of all the calls far in advance; just that there is a commitment to funding in energy innovation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. How should DECC ensure that its remaining capital allocation for low carbon innovat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ion will be spent wisely, after two years of under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">spend?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Funding for research activities should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to some extent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> be seen as an investment. The objective therefore should not be to spend a particular amount of money, but to target that investment at the projects that will offer the best return</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. By “return”, we do not simply refer to financial return.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The best solution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">would be to allow a system of banking and borrowing, tied to the long term general commitment to in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">novation funding discussed in Q5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. This would provide flexibility to enable the money to be used for the best projects in the long run and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">void distortion due to short term budget issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">7. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How is the Government maximising opportunity to learn from and partner with international partners within and beyond the EU?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Energy Research Partnership (ERP), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">which SSE is a member and co-chair,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is carrying out a piece of work on this topic. Various Government departments (including the other co-chair, DECC) and funding bodies are also members of ERP. It is expected to recommend a more strategic approach to identifying international collaboration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> opportunities, which should identify topics, partners and objectives along with UK parties to pursue these.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Briefing-for-ECC-Public-funding-for-innovation-in-low-carbon-technology.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Briefing-for-ECC-Public-funding-for-innovation-in-low-carbon-technology.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><a href="https://workspace.imperial.ac.uk/rcukenergystrategy/Public/reports/Final%20Reports/RCUK%20Brighter%20energy.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://workspace.imperial.ac.uk/rcukenergystrategy/Public/reports/Final%20Reports/RCUK%20Brighter%20energy.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; fon